1
00:00:01,100 --> 00:00:03,330
You saw in the last video,

2
00:00:03,330 --> 00:00:04,500
what are the states of

3
00:00:04,500 --> 00:00:06,405
reinforcement
learning application,

4
00:00:06,405 --> 00:00:08,850
as well as how depending
on the actions

5
00:00:08,850 --> 00:00:11,250
you take you go through
different states,

6
00:00:11,250 --> 00:00:14,190
and also get to enjoy
different rewards.

7
00:00:14,190 --> 00:00:17,490
But how do you know if a
particular set of rewards is

8
00:00:17,490 --> 00:00:20,520
better or worse than a
different set of rewards?

9
00:00:20,520 --> 00:00:22,830
The return in
reinforcement learning,

10
00:00:22,830 --> 00:00:24,345
which we'll define
in this video,

11
00:00:24,345 --> 00:00:26,325
allows us to capture that.

12
00:00:26,325 --> 00:00:27,645
As we go through this,

13
00:00:27,645 --> 00:00:29,910
one analogy that you
might find helpful

14
00:00:29,910 --> 00:00:31,800
is if you imagine

15
00:00:31,800 --> 00:00:33,870
you have a five-dollar
bill at your feet,

16
00:00:33,870 --> 00:00:35,340
you can reach down and pick up,

17
00:00:35,340 --> 00:00:37,785
or half an hour across town,

18
00:00:37,785 --> 00:00:41,025
you can walk half an hour and
pick up a 10-dollar bill.

19
00:00:41,025 --> 00:00:43,770
Which one would you
rather go after?

20
00:00:43,770 --> 00:00:47,085
Ten dollars is much
better than five dollars,

21
00:00:47,085 --> 00:00:48,900
but if you need to
walk for half an hour

22
00:00:48,900 --> 00:00:50,570
to go and get that
10-dollar bill,

23
00:00:50,570 --> 00:00:51,680
then maybe it'd be more

24
00:00:51,680 --> 00:00:54,575
convenient to just pick up
the five-dollar bill instead.

25
00:00:54,575 --> 00:00:58,730
The concept of a return captures
that rewards you can get

26
00:00:58,730 --> 00:01:00,740
quicker are maybe
more attractive than

27
00:01:00,740 --> 00:01:03,070
rewards that take you
a long time to get to.

28
00:01:03,070 --> 00:01:05,635
Let's take a look at
exactly how that works.

29
00:01:05,635 --> 00:01:08,055
Here's a Mars Rover example.

30
00:01:08,055 --> 00:01:11,345
If starting from state
4 you go to the left,

31
00:01:11,345 --> 00:01:14,030
we saw that the
rewards you get would

32
00:01:14,030 --> 00:01:16,715
be zero on the first
step from state 4,

33
00:01:16,715 --> 00:01:18,370
zero from state 3,

34
00:01:18,370 --> 00:01:19,815
zero from state 2,

35
00:01:19,815 --> 00:01:23,790
and then 100 at state
1, the terminal state.

36
00:01:23,790 --> 00:01:28,315
The return is defined as the sum

37
00:01:28,315 --> 00:01:32,305
of these rewards but weighted
by one additional factor,

38
00:01:32,305 --> 00:01:34,970
which is called the
discount factor.

39
00:01:34,970 --> 00:01:39,080
The discount factor is a number
a little bit less than 1.

40
00:01:39,080 --> 00:01:41,975
Let me pick 0.9 as
the discount factor.

41
00:01:41,975 --> 00:01:44,010
I'm going to weight the reward

42
00:01:44,010 --> 00:01:45,360
in the first step is just zero,

43
00:01:45,360 --> 00:01:48,100
the reward in the second
step is a discount factor,

44
00:01:48,100 --> 00:01:50,860
0.9 times that reward,

45
00:01:50,860 --> 00:01:54,940
and then plus the discount
factor^2 times that reward,

46
00:01:54,940 --> 00:01:59,335
and then plus the discount
factor^3 times that reward.

47
00:01:59,335 --> 00:02:00,880
If you calculate this out,

48
00:02:00,880 --> 00:02:08,540
this turns out to be 0.729
times 100, which is 72.9.

49
00:02:08,540 --> 00:02:13,280
The more general formula
for the return is that if

50
00:02:13,280 --> 00:02:15,620
your robot goes through
some sequence of

51
00:02:15,620 --> 00:02:19,475
states and gets reward
R_1 on the first step,

52
00:02:19,475 --> 00:02:21,620
and R_2 on the second step,

53
00:02:21,620 --> 00:02:24,035
and R_3 on the third step,

54
00:02:24,035 --> 00:02:25,805
and so on,

55
00:02:25,805 --> 00:02:31,875
then the return is R_1 plus
the discount factor Gamma,

56
00:02:31,875 --> 00:02:33,939
this Greek alphabet Gamma

57
00:02:33,939 --> 00:02:36,770
which I've set to
0.9 in this example,

58
00:02:36,770 --> 00:02:38,990
the Gamma times R_2

59
00:02:38,990 --> 00:02:43,490
plus Gamma^2 times R_3
plus Gamma^3 times R_4,

60
00:02:43,490 --> 00:02:48,115
and so on, until you get
to the terminal state.

61
00:02:48,115 --> 00:02:52,730
What the discount factor
Gamma does is it has

62
00:02:52,730 --> 00:02:55,010
the effect of making

63
00:02:55,010 --> 00:02:56,795
the reinforcement
learning algorithm

64
00:02:56,795 --> 00:02:58,370
a little bit impatient.

65
00:02:58,370 --> 00:03:01,670
Because the return
gives full credit to

66
00:03:01,670 --> 00:03:05,510
the first reward is 100
percent is 1 times R_1,

67
00:03:05,510 --> 00:03:08,090
but then it gives a
little bit less credit to

68
00:03:08,090 --> 00:03:09,755
the reward you get
at the second step

69
00:03:09,755 --> 00:03:11,585
is multiplied by 0.9,

70
00:03:11,585 --> 00:03:13,580
and then even less
credit to the reward you

71
00:03:13,580 --> 00:03:15,680
get at the next time step R_3,

72
00:03:15,680 --> 00:03:18,380
and so on, and so
getting rewards

73
00:03:18,380 --> 00:03:22,630
sooner results in a higher
value for the total return.

74
00:03:22,630 --> 00:03:25,155
In many reinforcement
learning algorithms,

75
00:03:25,155 --> 00:03:26,240
a common choice for

76
00:03:26,240 --> 00:03:29,495
the discount factor will be
a number pretty close to 1,

77
00:03:29,495 --> 00:03:34,890
like 0.9, or 0.99,
or even 0.999.

78
00:03:34,890 --> 00:03:36,820
But for illustrative purposes

79
00:03:36,820 --> 00:03:39,110
in the running example
I'm going to use,

80
00:03:39,110 --> 00:03:43,625
I'm actually going to use
a discount factor of 0.5.

81
00:03:43,625 --> 00:03:46,980
This very heavily
down weights or

82
00:03:46,980 --> 00:03:50,235
very heavily we say discounts
rewards in the future,

83
00:03:50,235 --> 00:03:53,480
because with every additional
parsing timestamp,

84
00:03:53,480 --> 00:03:55,820
you get only half
as much credit as

85
00:03:55,820 --> 00:03:59,380
rewards that you would have
gotten one step earlier.

86
00:03:59,380 --> 00:04:02,090
If Gamma were equal to 0.5,

87
00:04:02,090 --> 00:04:05,000
the return under the example
above would have been

88
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:09,305
0 plus 0.5 times 0,

89
00:04:09,305 --> 00:04:11,045
replacing this equation on top,

90
00:04:11,045 --> 00:04:17,965
plus 0.5^2 0 plus
0.5^3 times 100.

91
00:04:17,965 --> 00:04:21,660
That's lost reward because
state 1 to terminal state,

92
00:04:21,660 --> 00:04:26,100
and this turns out to
be a return of 12.5.

93
00:04:26,100 --> 00:04:30,110
In financial applications,
the discount factor also has

94
00:04:30,110 --> 00:04:32,240
a very natural interpretation as

95
00:04:32,240 --> 00:04:35,200
the interest rate or the
time value of money.

96
00:04:35,200 --> 00:04:38,225
If you can have a dollar today,

97
00:04:38,225 --> 00:04:40,910
that may be worth
a little bit more

98
00:04:40,910 --> 00:04:43,280
than if you could only get
a dollar in the future.

99
00:04:43,280 --> 00:04:46,225
Because even a dollar today
you can put in the bank,

100
00:04:46,225 --> 00:04:47,960
earn some interest,
and end up with

101
00:04:47,960 --> 00:04:50,080
a little bit more
money a year from now.

102
00:04:50,080 --> 00:04:52,235
For financial
applications, often,

103
00:04:52,235 --> 00:04:55,310
that discount factor
represents how much less

104
00:04:55,310 --> 00:04:56,870
is a dollar in the future where

105
00:04:56,870 --> 00:04:58,870
I've compared to a dollar today.

106
00:04:58,870 --> 00:05:02,650
Let's look at some concrete
examples of returns.

107
00:05:02,650 --> 00:05:05,855
The return you get
depends on the rewards,

108
00:05:05,855 --> 00:05:08,945
and the rewards depends
on the actions you take,

109
00:05:08,945 --> 00:05:12,860
and so the return depends
on the actions you take.

110
00:05:12,860 --> 00:05:17,615
Let's use our usual example
and say for this example,

111
00:05:17,615 --> 00:05:21,465
I'm going to always
go to the left.

112
00:05:21,465 --> 00:05:24,430
We already saw
previously that if

113
00:05:24,430 --> 00:05:27,985
the robot were to
start off in state 4,

114
00:05:27,985 --> 00:05:30,070
the return is 12.5 as

115
00:05:30,070 --> 00:05:32,415
we worked out on
the previous slide.

116
00:05:32,415 --> 00:05:37,250
It turns out that if it were
to start off in say three,

117
00:05:37,250 --> 00:05:40,490
the return would be
25 because it gets

118
00:05:40,490 --> 00:05:44,480
to the 100 reward
one step sooner,

119
00:05:44,480 --> 00:05:47,060
and so it's discounted less.

120
00:05:47,060 --> 00:05:49,430
If it were to start
off in state 2,

121
00:05:49,430 --> 00:05:51,320
the return would be 50.

122
00:05:51,320 --> 00:05:53,990
If it were to just start
off and state 1, well,

123
00:05:53,990 --> 00:05:56,420
it gets the reward
of 100 right away,

124
00:05:56,420 --> 00:05:57,965
so it's not discounted low.

125
00:05:57,965 --> 00:05:59,600
The return if we
were to start out in

126
00:05:59,600 --> 00:06:01,700
state 1 will be 100,

127
00:06:01,700 --> 00:06:05,450
and then the return in
these two states are 6.25.

128
00:06:05,450 --> 00:06:07,640
It turns out if you
start off in state 6,

129
00:06:07,640 --> 00:06:08,915
which is terminal state,

130
00:06:08,915 --> 00:06:14,135
you just get the reward
and thus the return of 40.

131
00:06:14,135 --> 00:06:17,390
Now, if you were to take a
different set of actions,

132
00:06:17,390 --> 00:06:20,345
the returns would
actually be different.

133
00:06:20,345 --> 00:06:25,100
For example, if we were to
always go to the right,

134
00:06:25,100 --> 00:06:26,884
if those were our actions,

135
00:06:26,884 --> 00:06:31,835
then if you were to start in
state 4, get a reward of 0.

136
00:06:31,835 --> 00:06:34,940
Then you get to state
5, get a reward of 0,

137
00:06:34,940 --> 00:06:36,485
and it gets to state 6,

138
00:06:36,485 --> 00:06:38,450
and get a reward of 40.

139
00:06:38,450 --> 00:06:43,235
In this case, the return
would be 0 plus 0.5,

140
00:06:43,235 --> 00:06:48,965
the discount factor times 0
plus 0.5 squared times 40,

141
00:06:48,965 --> 00:06:53,375
and that turns out to be
equal to 0.5 squared is 1/4,

142
00:06:53,375 --> 00:06:55,910
so 1/4 of 40 is 10.

143
00:06:55,910 --> 00:06:58,100
The return from this state,

144
00:06:58,100 --> 00:07:00,080
from state 4 is 10.

145
00:07:00,080 --> 00:07:01,190
If you were to take actions,

146
00:07:01,190 --> 00:07:03,275
always go to the right.

147
00:07:03,275 --> 00:07:05,045
Through similar reasoning,

148
00:07:05,045 --> 00:07:07,175
the return from
this state is 20,

149
00:07:07,175 --> 00:07:09,485
the return from
this state is five,

150
00:07:09,485 --> 00:07:12,425
the return from
this state is 2.5,

151
00:07:12,425 --> 00:07:13,760
and then the return,

152
00:07:13,760 --> 00:07:15,920
the determinant state is is 140.

153
00:07:15,920 --> 00:07:17,960
By the way,

154
00:07:17,960 --> 00:07:20,165
if these numbers don't
fully make sense,

155
00:07:20,165 --> 00:07:21,650
feel free to pause the video and

156
00:07:21,650 --> 00:07:23,360
double-check the
math and see if you

157
00:07:23,360 --> 00:07:25,355
can convince yourself that these

158
00:07:25,355 --> 00:07:27,815
are the appropriate
values for the return.

159
00:07:27,815 --> 00:07:30,230
For if you start from
different states,

160
00:07:30,230 --> 00:07:33,750
and if you were to
always go to the right.

161
00:07:33,750 --> 00:07:37,700
We see that it would
always go to the right.

162
00:07:37,700 --> 00:07:42,260
The return you expect to get
is lower for most states.

163
00:07:42,260 --> 00:07:44,675
Maybe always going
to the right isn't

164
00:07:44,675 --> 00:07:48,695
as good an idea as always
going to the left.

165
00:07:48,695 --> 00:07:50,690
But it turns out that we

166
00:07:50,690 --> 00:07:52,295
don't have to always
go to the left,

167
00:07:52,295 --> 00:07:53,885
always go to the right.

168
00:07:53,885 --> 00:07:57,740
We could also decide if
you're in state 2, go left.

169
00:07:57,740 --> 00:07:59,720
If your in state 3, go left.

170
00:07:59,720 --> 00:08:01,460
If you're in state 4, go left.

171
00:08:01,460 --> 00:08:03,020
But if you're in state 5,

172
00:08:03,020 --> 00:08:05,945
then you're so close
to this reward.

173
00:08:05,945 --> 00:08:07,670
Let's go right.

174
00:08:07,670 --> 00:08:10,955
This will be a different
way of choosing

175
00:08:10,955 --> 00:08:14,240
actions to take based on
what state you're in.

176
00:08:14,240 --> 00:08:17,750
It turns out that the return

177
00:08:17,750 --> 00:08:24,245
you get from the different
states will be 100, 50, 25,

178
00:08:24,245 --> 00:08:28,655
12.5, 20, and 40.

179
00:08:28,655 --> 00:08:31,790
Just to illustrate one case.

180
00:08:31,790 --> 00:08:34,235
If you were to start
off in state 5,

181
00:08:34,235 --> 00:08:35,930
here you would go to the right,

182
00:08:35,930 --> 00:08:38,090
and so the rewards
you get would be

183
00:08:38,090 --> 00:08:41,240
zero first in state
5, and then 4.

184
00:08:41,240 --> 00:08:44,750
The return is zero,
the first reward,

185
00:08:44,750 --> 00:08:49,355
plus the discount factor is
0.5 times 40, which is 20,

186
00:08:49,355 --> 00:08:51,260
which is why the return
from this status

187
00:08:51,260 --> 00:08:54,875
20 if you take
actions shown here.

188
00:08:54,875 --> 00:08:57,470
To summarize, the return in

189
00:08:57,470 --> 00:08:59,600
reinforcement
learning is the sum

190
00:08:59,600 --> 00:09:01,640
of the rewards that
the system gets,

191
00:09:01,640 --> 00:09:03,965
weighted by the discount factor,

192
00:09:03,965 --> 00:09:06,695
where rewards in the
far future are weighted

193
00:09:06,695 --> 00:09:10,175
by the discount factor
raised to a higher power.

194
00:09:10,175 --> 00:09:12,260
Now, this actually has

195
00:09:12,260 --> 00:09:14,090
an interesting
effect when you have

196
00:09:14,090 --> 00:09:16,160
systems with negative rewards.

197
00:09:16,160 --> 00:09:17,705
In the example we went through,

198
00:09:17,705 --> 00:09:20,615
all the rewards were
zero or positive.

199
00:09:20,615 --> 00:09:23,690
But if there are any
rewards are negative,

200
00:09:23,690 --> 00:09:25,700
then the discount
factor actually

201
00:09:25,700 --> 00:09:27,650
incentivizes the system to

202
00:09:27,650 --> 00:09:29,615
push out the negative rewards

203
00:09:29,615 --> 00:09:31,910
as far into the
future as possible.

204
00:09:31,910 --> 00:09:33,905
Taking a financial example,

205
00:09:33,905 --> 00:09:36,545
if you had to pay someone $10,

206
00:09:36,545 --> 00:09:39,290
maybe that's a negative
reward of minus 10.

207
00:09:39,290 --> 00:09:43,520
But if you could postpone
payment by a few years,

208
00:09:43,520 --> 00:09:44,930
then you're actually better off

209
00:09:44,930 --> 00:09:47,780
because $10 a few
years from now,

210
00:09:47,780 --> 00:09:50,540
because of the interest
rate is actually worth

211
00:09:50,540 --> 00:09:54,545
less than $10 that
you had to pay today.

212
00:09:54,545 --> 00:09:56,960
For systems with
negative rewards,

213
00:09:56,960 --> 00:09:59,705
it causes the algorithm
to try to push

214
00:09:59,705 --> 00:10:01,325
out the make the rewards

215
00:10:01,325 --> 00:10:03,530
as far into the
future as possible.

216
00:10:03,530 --> 00:10:06,350
For financial applications
and for other applications,

217
00:10:06,350 --> 00:10:07,670
that actually turns out

218
00:10:07,670 --> 00:10:09,230
to be right thing for
the system to do.

219
00:10:09,230 --> 00:10:11,630
You now know what

220
00:10:11,630 --> 00:10:13,870
is the return in
reinforcement learning,

221
00:10:13,870 --> 00:10:15,380
let's go on to the next video to

222
00:10:15,380 --> 00:10:19,260
formalize the goal of
